{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_kent_ver01/data/sn92051227/00415620767/1921020801/0471.xml":{"full_text":"SIX\nTHE TIMES: TUESDAY, FEBRUARY 8, 1921\nBigBemandFor\n(0verlancl,\n'L.J.\nSail\nMcCracken\nOne of the most optimistic of loca\ndealers in evidence at the Bridgepor.\nAutomobile Show last night was L. J.\nMcCracken, of the Overland-Mc-Cracken\nCompany, dealers in Over\nland and Willys-Knight cars.\nWhen a Times representative asked\nMr McCracken as to his view's on .the\nbusiness outlook Mr. McCracken de\nclared that production is gaining ev\nery day In most automobile plants.\nHe- said that manufacturers are be\nginning to think seriously about their\nability to meet the demand for cars,\nthat is indisputably indicated in an\nincreasing interest on the part of the\ngeneral public. ,Said Mr. McCracken:\n\"The world has been on short auto\nrations about as long as It can stand\nIt. Men who feel the need of an\nextraordinary effort in business, are\nAnding that they' can come back faster\nand quicker witn tbe aid or a car.\nThe world will speed up from now on\nto make up for time lost during tne\ndull days of the last few months.\nNothing picks up spee,d like an auto\nmobile. ii\nProduction Increasing.\n\"A survey of the auto manufactur\ning Held shows a resumption of activ\nity in the great automotive centers,\nwhich, while small compared with\npeak performances in the past, indi\ncates that the industry is coming out\nof hibernation and gathering head\nWay for normal business,\ni Local automobile dealers report\nmany signs of reviving popular in\nterest in automobile and truck lines.\"\n\"There is every indication that the\nyear just opening will be one of the\nmost eventful in the history of the\nautomotive industry,\" says Li. J. Mc\nCracken of the Overland-McCracken\nCompany, dealers in Overland and\nWillys-Knight cars.\n\"In 1919, we witnessed the basic\nreadjustment of the automobile trade\nconditions. The business -settled it\nself more squarely upon the universal\nfoundations of all merchandising.\nDuring the latter months of 1919,\nthere was a serious curtailment of\nproduction and distribution due, to a\ncertain extent, to national conditions.\nBut to the far-sighted manufacturer\nand dealer, the period through which\nthe Industry is passing has always\nloomed on the horizon and those of\nus who understand it are glad that it\nIs come and that we face what may\nbe called the permanent era of auto\nmoblling merchandising.\nCo-operation ITrsred.\n\"This evolution in automotive trade\nhas brought sharply into focus the\npersonal and individual responsibility\nor tbe dealer. It Has brought home\nto the owner the fact that his dealer\nrepresents the ability of his car to get\nsatisfaction, and It has sharply em\nphasized tne value of dealer service\nand co-operation. I look forward to\na remarkably brisk spring and sum\nmer season. The price of cars has\nnever been any real Influence with\nthe purchasing public. The man who\nwants an automobile is not merely\nouying a macmne. but is buying abil\nity of that machine to given him the\npleasure and service that he expects.\ncars today are mechanically per-\no4- 1 1, ..1 1 1 f\nautomotive engineering has progress\ned far past what would ordinarily be\nacnievea in a aecaae. .Dealers are\nrecognizing and accepting the obliga\ntion wnicn now rests squarely upon\nthem. There is going to be more\nsatisfaction in tne ownership of an\nautomobile than ever before has been\nObtained.\"\nFamily Automobiles.\n\"There's going to be less trouble\nwith the family auto from now on,'\nsays L. J. McCracken of the Overland\niiiraciten company, dealers ity\nuveriana ana Willys-Knight cars, \"be\ncause mother has formally assumed\nresponsibility ror Its behavior in\nmany Bridgeport households.\"\n\"The time israpidly passing when a\nwoman has to phone for help every\ntime the car balks. She is learning\nits mechanism with real engineering\nperception and she keeps the car\n\"tuned up .as efficiently as she keeps\nher house in order.\"\nThis interest in automotive me\nchanics among Bridgeport women is\ngeneral over the country. That the\npurr of a smooth-running motor is\nweeter to feminine ears than the rat\ntle of dishes is indicated by the action\nof the North Dakota Agricultural Col\nlege in establishing a department of\nAutomotive Mechanics in the College\nHome Demonstration Department.\nThis came about when North Dakota\nwomen yawned so much over a lec\nture on menu-building that the direc-\ntor asked them if there was any other\ntopic of home management which\nthey would rather hear discussed.\n\"We want to learn how to fix an\nautomobile when it won't run,\" an\nswered the women. So Mrs. Louis\nCampbell, the director, hired a new\ninstructor and started a course on\nblow-out repairs. The more difficult\nproblems will follow.\nNew Buyer's Opportunity.\n\"The new buyer is about the only\none who is sure of present market\nconditions,\" says L. J. McCracken of\nthe Overland-McCracken Company,\ndealers in Overland and Willys\nKnight cars.\n\"The man who owns a car Vnn\nthat wherever the car may be, his in\nvestment does not depreciate as long\nas the car is giving him satisfactory\nservice. He is not interested in a.mr\nfluctuation in price.\n\"He knows that if he wants a new\ncar, or a different car, the value o'f\nhis car as a 'trade-in' is not in any\ndegree affected by the price of the\nnew car. So the season's automobile\nowner is happily indifferent to the\nlatter of price which seems some\n.mes to the new buyer to be an item\njf solemn importance.\n\"I believe that an understanding of\nMs is becoming more general among\nthe army of prospects who are post\nponing irom day to aay tne acquiai\n.ion of the automobile which they\niiave long desired to own, and I am\nconfident that as soon as a clear un\nderstanding of this principle of auto\nmobile merchandising reaches the\npublic generally, no one will hesitate\nto buy an automobile.\n\"As a matter of fact, it seems im\npossible to conceive of any further\nreductions, but the oustanding idea\nso well known to those familiar with\nautomobiles is that the price really\ndoesn't make any difference, for the\nman who buys an automobile never\nexpects- to be without one. And his\nfirst investment, after a fashion, pays\nhis dues in the big lodge and puts him\nin a position at any time thereafter\nto have any car that he may want un\nder conditions that make him practi\ncally independent of the market.\"\nin travel, would all be within limits\nunknown to the automobile.\n\"And- there is the convenience at\ntached to one's own passenger car.-It\nis alwavs ready to ero not only to\nevery place any other conveyance will\ntake you, but to places only the auto\nmobile can comfortaDiy iranspgri\nyou.\nAll this adds to vnur efficiency. It\ndoes more to restore your fitness for\nbusiness.. It adds to the servici\nthrough which the motor car is be\ncoming ever more valuable to the\nbusiness- of the world.\nCredit must be given to those who\nforesaw this great opportunity for\nservice and provided the type of mo\ntor car that makes it possible to the\nmajority of people. Modern cars\nwere especially designed for (every\nday usefulness. They were made to\noperate aeonomically under 'all con\nditions and to sell at- a price which\nplaces their convenience within the\nmeans of practically every one.\nChevrolet Review.\nMotor Fatalities\nUnfairly Figured\nStatistics recently given' out by the\nNew Tork State Automobile Assdfcia\nton figures which have received\nwidespread publicity because Motor\nRow, on the ground that while they\nare accurate in themselves, they are\nmisleading to the public. Mr. Larson\nalso says he regrets that an asso\nciation which has done such admir\nable work for the motorist should\nput forth the statistics without suffi\ncient explanation.\n-\"The association points out,\" Mr.\nLarson declares, \"that the death toll\nin this State has mounted' from 600\nfatalities five years ago to 1,291 in\n1920, but it does not give figures on\nthe growth of the motor vehicles in\nNew York during that period.\n\"When these statistics are inspect\ned it is found that the past year New\nTork State had more than two and\none-half times as many automobiles\nit had in 1916. Of course, it Is\nnot to be expected and much\ndesired that the accident rate should\ncorrespond precisely with the rate of\nincrease in motor traffic. But In fair\nness to the motorist the public should\nunderstand that, after all, the chief\nand all-powerful reason for the jump\nin automobile fatalities ia the jump\nin automobile reglstratons.\n\"Furthermore, I do not believe that\nthere is much connection between the\naccident rate and the fact that the\nlaw now permits non-residents of\nthis city to operate for ten days in\nthe metropolis without a license. It\nwould be wise to change the law, as\nthe association suggests, but. the most\nimportant method of cutting down\naccidents and collisions is to keep up\na constant educational and safety-\nfirst campaign for both automobllist\nand pedestrian.\"\n-SAES X1XE.\"\n\"Look over your car at least once\na week. You'll take more comfort\nout of it and save money.\" is the sage\nadvice of J. D. Mansfield, general\nsales manager of the Doit Motor Car\nCompany.\nGASOLESK WASTEi\n\"Thirty per cent, of lb saaotena\nnow used by automobiles In (ha\nUnited States is wasted through de\nfects in carbureters,' according to\nDr. A. O. Fielder, supervising chem\nist In the United States Bureau at\nMines experiment station at Pitts\nburgh. Pa,\notor Trips Not\nAlways Strictly\nPleasure Jaunts\ni\now Chalmers Saves\ny Pre-Heating Fuel\nLAKEVIEW\nAUTO CO.\n860 BOSTON AVENUE.\nRepairing and overhauling of all makes of\ncars. All -work guaranteed.\nAuto\nV\nAccessories\nLighting, Starting arid Ignition systems in\nstalled and repaired.\nGarage Call Xoble 1476.\nLate night Calls Barnign 3432-15.\nGoodyear Tire Service Station.\nSluts Service Station.\nAutomobiles are used more for\nbusiness than anything else. And\nwhen we speak of businss we do not\nmean only those cars wheih are used\nin a strictly commercial sense. We\nrefer to all passenger cars in general\nuse.\nIt has been calculated that 80 per\ncent, of the cars which you see daily\nin'your own community are employed\nin the business of their owners.\nAside from the salesman's trip, the\ndoctor's call, the farmer's going to\nthe bank or market and return, you\nwill see passenger cars meeting\ntrains, taking women on shopping\ntours, carrying; messages or parcels\nfor private owners,- serving as the\nmost convenient quick method of\ntransportation whenever the need for\ntravel arises.\nEven the holiday tour or the even\ning ride out into the country or the\ntrip to the moving picture show, or\nto a neighbor's home for a social call,\ncannot be called strictly pleasure.\nOf course, the use of an automo\nbile affords pleasure. Any improved\nmethod of doing anything affords\npleasure. And the automobile gives\na vast amount of pleasure, because it\nis such a great improvement in trans\nportation.\nIt pleases the business man to save\ntime, money, and effort in getting\nfrom one place to another, in getting\nmore things done more efficiently.\nBut you do not call a commercial\nautomobile a pleasure car.\nSo it is with recreation. Only the\nremaining 20 per cent, of the service\nof passenger automobiles is given\nover to recreation alone. But this\nuse or motor vehicles is not strictly\na pleasure use. ..In such cases the\nowner uses his car as an improved\ntransportation utility.\nWithout an automobile of his own\nhe would have to depend on some\nother form of conveyance. In this\ncase, the distance and direction he\ncould go, the time he would consume\nMore than three years ago, Chalmers\nengineers began fighting poor gasoline.\nThey won by a simple means of heating\nthe vaporized fuel -mixture before it\nenters the motor cylinders.\nNote that we say heating the fuel, not\nmerely the air. There is a greatdifference.\nWhat this simple device does is told in\nthe report of a committee of the\nSociety of Automotive Engineers.'\nLess Fuel Used\nThis committee says pre-heating the\nfuel secures better combustion, with a\ndecrease in fuel consumption. A dis\ntinct saving.\nCrankcase dilution is decreased by\nlimiting the passage of unburned fuel\npast the pistons. An even greater saving.\nGasoline today is so poor that in ordi\nnary motors it is not all consumed.\nHence, raw, unburned gasoline seep\ndown past the pistons into the crank\ncase oil. The oil is diluted with gaso\nline. It loses its lubricating qualities.\nCostly Trouble Avoided\nThe next thing is motor trouble, such as\nscored cylinders,warped pistons, burned\nbearings, loosened wrist pins? etc., all of\nwhich Chalmers largely avoids.\nThe engine, says the committee, de\nlivers higher power over longer periods\nbetween overhauling. A great saving\nand a real comfort to the owner!\nPerformance is improved, and accelera\ntion made more smooth and more rapid.\nNow you see why Chalmers owners\nare so well satisfied.\nUnless you are getting the same or\nbetter results with your car, you should\ninvestigate the Chalmers at once.\nTHE STANDARD MOTORS CORPORATION\n2226 Fairfield Ave. at Whittier Street Tel. Etar. 4550\n\"For Your Own Satisfaction Ride with Us!\nRadiator\nRepairing\nBest Honeycomb cores installed in all makes.\nFirst-class work done on Fenders, Gas Tanks,\netc.\nFairfield Radiator\nRepair Company\n689 FAIRFIELD AVENUE.\nTel. Barnuni 6336. A. Buckler, Prop.\nS3\nUILOERS OF\nr\nWagons and Automobile Bo\nAuto Painting a Specialty\nRepairing and Painting in All Its Branches.\n22 COLOR ADO AVE.\ndies\nuse\nUSED GARS OF EVERY\nDESCRIPTION FOR SALE\nSome Good Bargains in Light Delivery Models\nAll in First Class Condition and Priced Right\nBridgeport Rebuilt Car Co.\n110 North Washington Ave. Phone Noble 2116\nNear Railroad Ave. Bar. 1374.\nBridgeport, Conn.\n'j\nALLAG\nTouring And Closed Body Trimmings, Tops And Seat Covers\nAsk To See Our New Tour Sedan Top\nRepairing A Speciality\n726 HOWARD AVENUE\nTELEPHONE BAKNTJM 22572\nGEO. E. WALLACE, Prop.\nFred SL Munson\nAuto Repairs\nStorage and\nSupplies\n210 CHARLES STREET\ni\nGarage Phone Barnrnn 1679-3.\nHouse Phone Bamum 1679-2.\n'i\nk\nS3\n3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\n3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3\nS3","height":"26656","width":"21684"}}
